ðŸ” What is a **ReplicationController** in Kubernetes?

A **ReplicationController (RC)** is a **legacy Kubernetes object** that ensures a **specified number of pod replicas are always running**.

---

âœ… **Main Purpose**

To **maintain pod availability** â€” if a pod goes down or is deleted, the RC automatically creates a new one to replace it.

---

ðŸ› ï¸ **Key Features**

| Feature                | Description                                                     |
| ---------------------  | --------------------------------------------------------------- |
| ðŸ” **Self-healing**    | Ensures the desired number of pods are always running.          |
| âž• **Scaling**         | You can increase/decrease the number of replicas dynamically.   |
| ðŸ” **Pod Management**  | Selects pods using a **label selector**.                        |
| ðŸ“¦ **Template**        | Contains the pod definition (metadata, spec, containers, etc.). |

---

ðŸ“„ Example Use Case

You want **3 instances of an NGINX server** running all the time. If one fails, the RC spins up a new one automatically to keep the count at 3.

---

âš ï¸ Deprecation Note

> ðŸ”¹ **ReplicationController is now considered legacy.**
> ðŸ”¸ Most modern Kubernetes deployments use **Deployments**, which offer more features like rolling updates and rollback.

---

ðŸ“Œ Summary

* ReplicationController keeps a **fixed number of identical pods** running.
* It uses a **selector** to match the pods it manages.
* Mostly replaced by **Deployments**, which are more powerful and flexible.
